       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="overview" class="section section--white">
    <div class="section__inner">
      <div class="overview-grid">
        <div class="overview__text">
          <h2>A Realistic Guide to Sulawesi's Fragile Archipelago</h2>

          <p>
            The wooden boat smelled of clove cigarettes and dried fish, a scent
            that seems to permeate every harbor in Sulawesi. We were sitting on
            plastic stools on the open deck of a public ferry leaving Luwuk,
            watching the mainland fade into a haze of humidity. Ahead of us lay
            the Banggai Archipelago, a cluster of islands that has recently
            drifted into the peripheral vision of the adventurous travel
            circuit.
          </p>

          <p>
            Most people come here for one reason: <strong>Lake Paisupok</strong
            >. You have likely seen the photos-a body of water so glassy and
            distinctively blue that it looks like a swimming pool dropped into a
            jungle. It is the image that launched a thousand Instagram saves.
          </p>

          <p>
            But the reality of the Banggai Islands is far more complex, and far
            less polished, than a single drone shot suggests. This is not the
            next Raja Ampat, nor is it a bite-sized version of Bali. It is a <strong
              >remote regency in Central Sulawesi</strong
            > where tourism is still an awkward, fledgling concept. Infrastructure
            is brittle. English is rarely spoken. The electricity grid is a part-time
            participant in daily life.
          </p>

          <p>
            We spent two weeks moving between Peleng, Banggai Laut, and the
            smaller satellites. We found a region of quiet beauty and
            frustrating logistics. It is a place where you might swim in the
            clearest water of your life in the morning and spend the afternoon
            stranded on a roadside because a petrol station ran dry.
          </p>

          <p>
            If you are patient, self-sufficient, and willing to trade comfort
            for silence, the Banggai Islands are remarkable. If you are looking
            for seamless transfers and air-conditioned cafes, you should
            probably stop reading here.
          </p>

          <p>
            This guide is a documentation of how we did it, what went wrong, and
            what we would do differently.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="overview__image">
          <Image
            src={wayagAerial}
            alt={"Islands of the Banggai Archipelago, Central Sulawesi"}
          />
          <p class="overview__image-caption">
            The Banggai Archipelago-quiet beauty and challenging logistics
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURED QUOTE - Full Width -->
