  <!-- UNDERSTANDING THE DESTINATION + PHOTO -->
  <section class="section section--white">
    <div class="section__inner">
      <div class="two-col-with-image">
        <div class="two-col-with-image__text">
          <h3>Understanding the Destination</h3>

          <p>
            <strong>Geography and Layout:</strong> The archipelago is split into two
            main administrative regencies: Banggai Kepulauan (Bangkep) and Banggai
            Laut (Balut). <strong>Peleng Island</strong> (Bangkep) is the massive,
            mountainous island closest to the mainland-home to Lake Paisupok, the
            jellyfish lagoon, and most tourist accommodation; the capital is Salakan.
            <strong>Banggai Island</strong> (Balut) lies further south and east, the
            historical center of the Banggai Kingdom, more maritime and culturally
            distinct. Labobo and Bokan are smaller islands offering incredible reefs
            and isolation, but requiring significant effort to reach.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Access and Gateways:</strong> There is no airport on the islands
            for commercial jets from Jakarta or Bali. The gateway is <strong
              >Luwuk (LWK)</strong
            > on the Sulawesi mainland. You typically fly into Luwuk (usually via
            Makassar), take a taxi to the harbor, and ferry across to Peleng Island.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>The Budget Reality:</strong> While Indonesia is generally cheap,
            remote Indonesia is surprisingly expensive. Logistics cost money. Accommodation:
            250,000-400,000 IDR (16-26 USD) per night for a basic room. Food: 30,000-60,000
            IDR (2-4 USD) per meal. Transport is the budget killer: a car charter
            can cost 700,000 IDR (45 USD) per day; boat charters to outlying islands
            can run from 800,000 to 1,500,000 IDR (50-100 USD) depending on fuel prices.
            You need cash. We found ATMs in Luwuk and Salakan (the capital of Peleng),
            and one lonely machine in Banggai town that rejected our cards. Once you
            leave the main towns, cash is the only way to pay.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="two-col-with-image__image">
          <Image src={coralReef} alt="Coastal waters of the Banggai Islands" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE MIRROR LAKE & BEYOND - Full Width Feature -->
  <section class="beyond-section">
    <div class="beyond-section__inner">
      <div class="beyond-section__content">
        <span class="beyond-section__label">Peleng Island</span>
        <h2>Lake Paisupok & the Jellyfish Lagoon</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Paisupok Lake</strong> is genuinely shocking-the water is so clear
          you can see every submerged log and rock fifty feet down. The color is not
          a filter; it is a deep, impossible turquoise. We walked down a dirt track
          and paid the entrance fee (15,000 IDR). We rented a small canoe (30,000
          IDR); this is mandatory if you want to get away from the main dock. We paddled
          out to the center of the lake. It was dead silent. The jungle overhangs
          the water, and because the lake is freshwater but connected to the sea via
          underground tunnels, there are no waves. It is like floating on glass. The
          wooden boardwalks that zigzag across the western end are slippery with moss
          and missing planks in places-watch your step. Go on a weekday; on Sundays,
          locals from Salakan flood the area with karaoke speakers and picnic baskets.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the afternoon we rented a scooter (100,000 IDR) to explore the
          coast. The road east of Luk Panenteng is rough; potholes are the size
          of dinner plates. We passed small fishing hamlets where children
          screamed "Hello Mister!" with frantic enthusiasm. We found a small
          cove with white sand, but as is common in Indonesia, the high tide
          line was choked with plastic waste-bottles, wrappers, flip-flops. It's
          a heartbreaking reality that is impossible to edit out of the
          experience.
        </p>
        <p>
          About 30 minutes from Luk Panenteng is <strong>Paisubatango</strong>,
          a lagoon home to stingless jellyfish-smaller and murkier than Raja
          Ampat's or Kakaban's, but thousands of them pulsating quietly in the
          green gloom. A local farmer pointed us toward a muddy path through a
          cocoa plantation; the walk took 15 minutes and was humid enough to
          soak our clothes instantly. Do not wear sunscreen or insect repellent
          here; the chemicals kill the jellyfish. We saw an oil slick on the
          surface near the entry point, likely from previous tourists. Nearby <strong
            >Paisu Pok</strong
          > is a freshwater cave pool-freezing cold and often empty; the "facilities"
          consisted of a broken wooden bench. Back at the homestay, the power didn't
          come on at 6:00 PM once-the generator had a mechanical issue. We ate dinner
          by the light of our headlamps. The power kicked in at 9:00 PM, and the village
          cheered.
        </p>
        <div class="beyond-section__highlights">
          <div class="beyond-section__highlight">
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-title">Paisupok Lake</div>
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-text">
              Early morning canoe; avoid weekends for serenity
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="beyond-section__highlight">
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-title">Paisubatango</div>
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-text">
              Stingless jellyfish lagoon; no sunscreen
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="beyond-section__highlight">
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-title">Paisu Pok</div>
            <div class="beyond-section__highlight-text">
              Freshwater cave pool; cold and quiet
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="beyond-section__image">
        <Image
          src={wayagAerial}
          alt="Lake Paisupok and the islands of Peleng"
