  <section id="logistics" class="section section--snow">
    <div class="section__inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-header__label">Travel Logistics</span>
        <h2 class="section-header__title">Getting to the Banggai Islands</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="logistics-two-col">
        <!-- Gateway & Routes -->
        <div class="flight-table">
          <div class="flight-table__header">
            <span class="flight-table__col-label">Route</span>
            <span class="flight-table__col-label">Details</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Fly to Luwuk (LWK)</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Usually via Makassar <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >from Jakarta/Bali</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Taxi → Luwuk Harbor</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Ignore touts <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >flag a car at gate</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Wooden boat → Leme-Leme</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >~2 PM daily <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >3-4 hrs, cheap</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Fast boat → Salakan</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Fiberglass <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >expensive, 2 hrs drive to lake</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Leme-Leme → Luk Panenteng</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Pre-arrange pickup <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >20 min drive</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Salakan → Banggai Town</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Daily wooden boat 2 PM <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >50K IDR, 3-4 hrs</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flight-table__row">
            <span class="flight-table__city">Banggai → Luwuk (return)</span>
            <span class="flight-table__time"
              >Speedboat ~8 AM <span class="flight-table__stops"
                >250K IDR, 3.5 hrs</span
              ></span
            >
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Content Side -->
        <div class="logistics-content">
          <div class="logistics-content__block">
            <h3 class="logistics-content__title">Reaching Luwuk</h3>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              There is no airport on the islands for commercial jets from
              Jakarta or Bali. The gateway is <strong>Luwuk (LWK)</strong> on the
              Sulawesi mainland. Fly into Luwuk (usually via Makassar), take a taxi
              to the harbor, and ferry across to Peleng Island. From Peleng you move
              deeper into the archipelago by boat.
            </p>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              <strong>You need cash.</strong> ATMs in Luwuk and Salakan (capital of
              Peleng), and one lonely machine in Banggai Town that rejected our cards.
              Once you leave main towns, cash is the only way to pay. Bring all the
              cash you think you need, then add 30%. ATMs often run out of money or
              reject foreign cards due to connection errors. We almost got stuck in
              Banggai Town because the BNI ATM was down for two days; we luckily had
              emergency USD we exchanged at a gold shop at a terrible rate.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="logistics-content__block">
            <h3 class="logistics-content__title">Scooters & Local Transport</h3>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              Rentals are informal-you are renting someone's personal bike.
              Check the brakes. Check the tires (many are bald). Helmets are
              often not provided or are cracked plastic shells. Petrol is sold
              in glass Absolut Vodka bottles at roadside shacks (Pertamini).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="logistics-content__block">
            <h3 class="logistics-content__title">
              Accommodation: The Honest Breakdown
            </h3>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              Accommodation in the Banggai Islands is functional, not
              experiential. You are paying for a roof, not a vibe.
            </p>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              <strong>Luk Panenteng (Peleng):</strong> Rustic homestays-usually a
              row of rooms facing the sea or the road. The walls are thin plywood;
              you will hear your neighbour snoring, the geckos fighting, and the generator
              humming. Sheets were clean but worn. The bathrooms are wet rooms (toilet,
              shower bucket, sink in one tiled space); the floor is perpetually wet.
              Food is included because there are no restaurants-expect fish, rice,
              noodles, and eggs. If you are vegetarian, you will eat a lot of eggs
              and kangkung. Most are not on Booking.com; find them on Google Maps
              and WhatsApp the owner. Use Google Translate.
            </p>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              <strong>Salakan (Peleng):</strong> Government worker transit hotels.
              Sterile, tiled, fluorescent lighting. Cleaner than village homestays
              but zero charm. Usually have AC and TV.
            </p>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              <strong>Banggai Town (Banggai Laut):</strong> Faded glory-old hotels
              with heavy wooden furniture and high ceilings. Some rooms have no windows;
              ask to see the room before paying. Check the AC unit-if it looks brown
              and ancient, it probably just blows fan air.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="logistics-content__block">
            <h3 class="logistics-content__title">Language & Connectivity</h3>
            <p class="logistics-content__text">
              English is virtually non-existent outside a few guides. Use Google
              Translate offline; learn basic Bahasa (e.g. kanan/kiri, mahal, jam
              berapa?). <strong>Telkomsel</strong> is the only carrier that matters;
              4G in Salakan and Banggai Town, 3G or Edge in Luk Panenteng. Download
              offline maps.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="logistics-stats">
            <div class="logistics-stats__item">
              <span class="logistics-stats__value">LWK</span>
              <span class="logistics-stats__label">Gateway Airport</span>
            </div>
            <div class="logistics-stats__item">
              <span class="logistics-stats__value">Cash</span>
              <span class="logistics-stats__label">Essential</span>
            </div>
            <div class="logistics-stats__item">
              <span class="logistics-stats__value">Telkomsel</span>
              <span class="logistics-stats__label">Best coverage</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PRACTICAL ADVICE - What We Learned
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="section section--deep">
    <div class="section__inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-header__label">Practical Advice</span>
        <h2 class="section-header__title">What We Learned</h2>
        <p class="section-header__subtitle">
          Tips that make the difference between a tough trip and a memorable
          one.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="insider-grid">
        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={mantaRays} alt="Dry bag for boats" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">Bring a Dry Bag</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              Between open boats, sudden downpours, and slippery docks, your
              gear will get wet. A 20L dry bag is essential for camera and
              passport.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={softCoralMangrove} alt="Mosquito management" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">Mosquito Management</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              Dengue is a risk in Sulawesi. Mosquitoes in Luk Panenteng are
              aggressive at dusk. Burn coils, wear long linen; bring DEET-hard
              to find there.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={wayagAerial} alt="Jam karet" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">"Rubber Time" (Jam Karet)</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              If a boat driver says 8:00 AM, he may mean he'll wake at 8, have
              coffee, buy fuel, and find you at 9:30. Do not plan tight
              connections.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={karstTurquoise} alt="Snacks" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">Snacks Are Salvation</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              Food is repetitive. Village kiosks sell mostly sweet biscuits.
              Bring nuts, protein bars, or whatever comfort food you need.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={heroPhinisi} alt="Snorkel gear" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">Snorkel Gear</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              Rental gear is often moldy, leaks, or has bitten-off mouthpieces.
              Bring your own mask and snorkel. Fins can be rented; mask is
              personal.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insider-card">
          <div class="insider-card__image">
            <Image src={coralReef} alt="Waste" />
          </div>
          <div class="insider-card__content">
            <h3 class="insider-card__title">Waste</h3>
            <p class="insider-card__text">
              No formal trash disposal in villages. Carry plastic back to Luwuk.
              If you leave it in the village bin, it will likely be burned or
              dumped in the river.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       ITINERARIES - Banggai Islands
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="itineraries" class="section section--cream">
    <div class="section__inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-header__label">Sample Itineraries</span>
        <h2 class="section-header__title">Banggai Islands Itineraries</h2>
        <p class="section-header__subtitle">
          A realistic 6-day loop (Peleng + Banggai Laut) or a shorter 4-5 day
          highlights-only focus on Peleng and the lake.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="itin-grid">
        <div class="itin-medium">
          <div class="itin-medium__image">
            <Image src={wayagAerial} alt="6-day Banggai loop" />
            <div class="itin-medium__badge">Full Loop</div>
            <div class="itin-medium__duration">
              <div class="itin-medium__duration-number">6</div>
              <div class="itin-medium__duration-label">Days</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="itin-medium__content">
            <span class="itin-medium__destination">Peleng + Banggai Laut</span>
            <h3 class="itin-medium__name">The Full 6-Day Loop</h3>
            <p class="itin-medium__tagline">
              Peleng (lake, jellyfish, cave) then ferry to Banggai Laut for
              Cardinalfish, island hopping, King's Bath and night market; return
              by speedboat to Luwuk.
            </p>
            <p class="itin-medium__route">
              Luwuk → Peleng → Banggai Laut → Luwuk
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="itin-medium">
          <div class="itin-medium__image">
            <Image src={coralReef} alt="4-5 day highlights" />
            <div class="itin-medium__badge">Highlights Only</div>
            <div class="itin-medium__duration">
              <div class="itin-medium__duration-number">4-5</div>
              <div class="itin-medium__duration-label">Days</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="itin-medium__content">
            <span class="itin-medium__destination">Peleng only</span>
            <h3 class="itin-medium__name">Shorter "Highlights Only" Loop</h3>
            <p class="itin-medium__tagline">
              Lake Paisupok and jellyfish lagoon, then island hop or coastal
              scooter; drive to Salakan and return to Luwuk. Skip Banggai Laut.
            </p>
            <p class="itin-medium__route">
              Luwuk → Luk Panenteng → Salakan → Luwuk
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="two-col-text" style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <div>
          <h3>Day 1: The Crossing</h3>
          <p>
            Route: Luwuk Airport → Luwuk Harbor → Leme-Leme (Peleng) → Luk
            Panenteng. We landed in Luwuk around midday, ignored the taxi touts
            and flagged a car to the ferry terminal. Two options: the public
            wooden boat to Leme-Leme (slow, 3-4 hours, cheap) or the fast boat
            to Salakan (expensive, then 2 hours drive to the lake). We chose the
            wooden boat; it departs daily around 2:00 PM-"2:00 PM" is a
            suggestion. We sat on the roof with the locals; the sea was calm but
            the boat is loud. We docked in Leme-Leme just before sunset; no
            taxis-pre-arrange pickup to Luk Panenteng. 20-minute drive through
            dense coconut plantations. Homestay: concrete room, mattress on
            floor, mosquito net; electricity 6 PM-6 AM only; mandi style, cold
            water. Cost: 350,000 IDR ($23 USD) including three meals.
          </p>

          <h3>Day 2: The Mirror Lake (Paisupok)</h3>
          <p>
            We woke at 5:30 AM. Paisupok Lake is a 10-minute walk from the
            homestays; entrance 15,000 IDR. We rented a canoe (30,000 IDR) and
            paddled to the center-dead silent, like floating on glass. By 11:00
            AM the sun was blistering; we retreated for lunch (grilled fish and
            kangkung-this became our diet for the week). Afternoon: scooter
            rental (100,000 IDR) east along rough roads, fishing hamlets, and a
            small cove (plastic waste at the high tide line).
          </p>

          <h3>Day 3: Jellyfish and Caves</h3>
          <p>
            Paisubatango (stingless jellyfish lagoon) about 30 minutes
            away-muddy path through a cocoa plantation, 15 minutes humid walk.
            Then Paisu Pok, a freezing freshwater cave pool; we were the only
            ones there. That evening the power didn't come on at 6 PM; the
            generator had a mechanical issue. We ate dinner by headlamp; the
            host brought extra tea. Power came on at 9:00 PM and the village
            cheered.
          </p>

          <h3>Day 4: Moving South to Banggai Laut</h3>
          <p>
            Luk Panenteng → Salakan (2 hours by pre-arranged driver; the road
            improves near the capital-Salakan has Indomarets and a traffic
            light). Daily wooden boat from Salakan to Banggai Town departs 2:00
            PM; 50,000 IDR per person; 3-4 hours. The crossing was rougher; we
            crossed open water where currents meet; passengers were vomiting
            into plastic bags. Banggai Town feels totally different-maritime,
            dense, built to the water's edge, mosques and houses on stilts. We
            stayed at a hotel near the harbor: AC, private bathroom with shower
            (cold water), Wi-Fi for WhatsApp. Cost: 300,000 IDR ($20 USD).
          </p>

          <h3>Day 5: The Cardinal Fish & The King's Bath</h3>
          <p>
            We walked to the main jetty in Banggai Town and looked down between
            the pilings-hundreds of Banggai Cardinalfish among the sea urchins
            under the busy dock. We chartered a boat for the day (800,000 IDR):
            Bone Baru (fine white sand, vibrant table and soft corals), Mandel
            (saw a turtle; current was strong). Back on Banggai Island we took
            an ojek to the King's Bath (Pemandian Raja)-freshwater spring once
            reserved for royalty, now a public swimming hole; cool and clear but
            concrete covered in moss and some litter. Dinner at the Night Market
            (Pasar Malam) near the harbor: grilled fish with dabu-dabu. Best
            meal of the trip. Cost: 40,000 IDR for a whole fish and rice.
          </p>

          <h3>Day 6: The Long Road Back</h3>
          <p>
            Speedboat from Banggai to Luwuk direct: 250,000 IDR per person,
            supposedly departs 8:00 AM. Long narrow fiberglass tube, windows
            sealed; 3.5 hours, bone-jarring. We checked into a hotel in Luwuk
            for the night-hot shower and a predictable electrical grid.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Shorter 4-5 Day Itinerary (Highlights Only)</h3>
          <p>
            If you don't have a week, skip Banggai Laut and focus on Peleng.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Day 1:</strong> Fly to Luwuk AM. Ferry to Leme-Leme. Sleep Luk
            Panenteng.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Day 2:</strong> Paisupok Lake (early AM). Paisubatango (Jellyfish)
            PM.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Day 3:</strong> Island hopping around Luk Panenteng (Poco Island)
            or coastal scooter ride.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Day 4:</strong> Morning swim. Drive to Salakan. Ferry or speedboat
            to Luwuk.
          </p>
          <p><strong>Day 5:</strong> Fly out.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-footer">
        <a href="/itineraries" class="section-footer__link"
          >EXPLORE ALL ITINERARIES →</a
        >
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

